.TH MONTECARLO 1 "2026-06-23" "finance/planning/annuity" "Annuity Planning Tools"
.SH NAME
montecarlo \- Monte Carlo confidence intervals for annuity-equivalent withdrawals
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B python montecarlo.py
.I amount age gender state
.RB [ --joint-age
.IR AGE ]
.RB [ --joint-gender
.IR M|F ]
.RB [ --sims
.IR N ]
.RB [ --years
.IR N ]
.RB [ --inflation
.IR RATE ]
.RB [ --model
.IR bootstrap|block|lognormal ]
.RB [ --block-length
.IR YEARS ]
.RB [ --quotes
.IR local|site ]
.RB [ --interest
.IR RATE ]
.RB [ --improvement ]
.RB [ --quote-year
.IR YEAR ]
.RB [ --upper-bound
.IR FACTOR ]
.RB [ --lower-bound
.IR FACTOR ]
.RB [ --seed
.IR INT ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B montecarlo.py
runs many random paths of the annuity-equivalent withdrawal model implemented in
.BR withdrawal_projection (1)
and reports the distribution of outcomes. For both the ending balance and the
yearly payout (the annual amount, i.e. the monthly payout times 12) it prints the
mean, the median, and the 80%, 90%, 95%, and 99% confidence intervals.
.PP
Each path applies the same strategy: keep the money invested in equities and each
year withdraw twelve times the life-annuity payout priced for the current balance
and age (see
.BR withdrawal_projection (1)
for the full description). Inflation is a single constant rate
.RB ( --inflation ,
default 2.5%); equity returns are drawn from the model selected by
.B --model
and restated onto that constant-inflation basis, so historical inflation has no
residual effect on equity. The per-year payout table is reported in today's
(inflation-deflated) dollars; the ending-balance section shows both nominal and
today's dollars.
.PP
The optional
.B --upper-bound
and
.B --lower-bound
factors cap and floor each path's annual withdrawal in today's dollars, relative
to that path's first-year withdrawal (see
.BR withdrawal_projection (1)).
.PP
Annuity payouts are priced by default from the local SOA-table model
.RB ( annuity_pricing (1),
offline);
.B --quotes site
uses live immediateannuities.com quotes instead. Either way the rate cache is
built once and reused across every path, so pricing cost (and any network
traffic) stays at roughly one rate per age regardless of the number of
simulations. With local pricing the startup cost is negligible.
.SH CONFIDENCE INTERVALS
A "C% confidence interval" is the central interval covering C% of the simulated
outcomes \(em the
.RI [ (100\-C)/2 ", " 100\-(100\-C)/2 ]
percentile range:
.IP \(bu 2
80% interval = 10th to 90th percentile
.IP \(bu 2
90% interval = 5th to 95th percentile
.IP \(bu 2
95% interval = 2.5th to 97.5th percentile
.IP \(bu 2
99% interval = 0.5th to 99.5th percentile
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.I amount
Starting amount invested (premium). Accepts plain digits, commas, or a leading
"$" (e.g. \fB1000000\fR, \fB1,000,000\fR). Must be positive.
.TP
.I age
Age today. Integer 40\(en90.
.TP
.I gender
\fBM\fR or \fBF\fR (\fBmale\fR/\fBfemale\fR also accepted).
.TP
.I state
Two-letter US state code, e.g. \fBFL\fR, or \fBOTHER\fR. Only used with
\fB--quotes site\fR (local pricing is state-independent), but always required on
the command line.
.TP
.BI --joint-age " AGE"
Age of a joint (second) beneficiary, 40\(en90. Switches to a joint-life annuity.
Must be given together with \fB--joint-gender\fR.
.TP
.BI --joint-gender " M|F"
Gender of the joint beneficiary. Must be given together with \fB--joint-age\fR.
.TP
.BI --sims " N"
Number of simulated paths. Default \fB5000\fR. Must be at least 2.
.TP
.BI --years " N"
Number of years to project per path. Default \fB30\fR.
.TP
.BI --inflation " RATE"
Constant annual inflation rate as a decimal fraction (e.g. \fB0.025\fR for
2.5%). Used to deflate results to today's dollars and to restate equity returns.
Default \fB0.025\fR.
.TP
.BI --model " bootstrap|block|lognormal"
Equity return model (see \fBwithdrawal_projection\fR(1) for details).
Default \fBbootstrap\fR.
.TP
.BI --block-length " YEARS"
Block size in years, used only with \fB--model block\fR. Default \fB5\fR.
.TP
.BI --quotes " local|site"
Annuity pricing source. \fBlocal\fR (default) prices from the SOA mortality
tables via \fBannuity_pricing\fR(1) \(em offline, honouring \fB--interest\fR and
\fB--improvement\fR. \fBsite\fR fetches live immediateannuities.com quotes
(requires network).
.TP
.BI --interest " RATE"
Flat annual interest rate for local pricing, as a decimal fraction. Used only
with \fB--quotes local\fR. Default \fB0.035\fR.
.TP
.B --improvement
Apply SOA Projection Scale G2 mortality improvement. Used only with
\fB--quotes local\fR; requires the G2 tables \fBsoa_mortality_2583.csv\fR and
\fBsoa_mortality_2584.csv\fR.
.TP
.BI --quote-year " YEAR"
Calendar year to project mortality to for \fB--improvement\fR. Default: current
year.
.TP
.BI --upper-bound " FACTOR"
Cap each path's annual withdrawal, in today's dollars, at this factor of that
path's first-year withdrawal (e.g. \fB1.2\fR). Must be positive. Default: no cap.
.TP
.BI --lower-bound " FACTOR"
Floor each path's annual withdrawal, in today's dollars, at this factor of that
path's first-year withdrawal (e.g. \fB0.5\fR). Must be non-negative and not
exceed \fB--upper-bound\fR. Default: no floor.
.TP
.BI --seed " INT"
Seed for the random number generator, for reproducible runs. Default: random.
.SH OUTPUT
In order:
.IP \(bu 2
A calibration header for the chosen model (sample span; equity arithmetic and
geometric mean and standard deviation; CPI mean and standard deviation;
equity/inflation correlation) and a line echoing the run parameters and elapsed
time.
.IP \(bu 2
.B Ending balance \(em today's dollars:
mean, median, and the four confidence intervals, followed by the worst
single-year and worst cumulative five-year
.I real
(inflation-adjusted) equity total return observed anywhere in the simulation,
shown as percentages.
.IP \(bu 2
.B Ending balance \(em nominal dollars:
the same statistics, undeflated.
.IP \(bu 2
A downside line: the percentage of paths whose real ending balance finishes below
the starting amount, and below half of it.
.IP \(bu 2
.B Annual payout by year:
a table with one row per projected year (year, age, mean, median, and the four
confidence intervals) for the annual payout (monthly x 12), in today's
(inflation-deflated) dollars.
.SH FILE EXPORT
When standard input is a terminal, after printing the report the program prompts:
.RS
.PP
.nf
Save output to a file? [PDF / csv / exit]:
.fi
.RE
.PP
Type \fBPDF\fR to write a PDF, \fBcsv\fR to write a CSV, or \fBexit\fR (or just
press Enter) to finish. Each choice asks for a filename and offers a default.
After a file is written the prompt repeats, so several files can be saved in one
run; it keeps asking until \fBexit\fR is entered. The prompt is skipped entirely
when input is not a terminal (e.g. piped or redirected), so scripted runs are
unaffected.
.PP
The \fBPDF\fR is a landscape report containing the full output: the username and
local date/time at the top, the two ending-balance tables (today's and nominal
dollars) side by side, and the annual-payout table below them. If the report
spans more than one page, the username and date/time are repeated, with a page
counter, in the footer of every page after the first.
.PP
The \fBCSV\fR contains the ending-balance summary (both bases, with the worst-
return figures) and the full per-year payout table, as numeric rows suitable for
a spreadsheet.
.SH NOTES
.IP \(bu 2
This models withdrawing the annuity-\fIequivalent\fR amount while staying invested
in equities; it is \fBnot\fR an annuity purchase (no mortality pooling, no income
guarantee). Because the full annuity payout includes return of principal, the
withdrawal rate is high and the real balance typically erodes over time \(em often
finishing below the starting amount. This is expected model behavior.
.IP \(bu 2
Local pricing (the default) uses the SOA 2012 IAM tables at a flat
\fB--interest\fR rate with no insurer expense or profit load, and handles any
age. With \fB--quotes site\fR, quote ages above 90 are clamped to the age-90
payout rate (the site's maximum) and network access to immediateannuities.com is
required for the startup quotes.
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Default 5000-path run:
.PP
.RS
.nf
python montecarlo.py 1000000 65 M FL
.fi
.RE
.PP
Local pricing at 4% interest with Scale G2 mortality improvement:
.PP
.RS
.nf
python montecarlo.py 1000000 65 M FL --interest 0.04 --improvement
.fi
.RE
.PP
2000 paths with live site quotes, the block bootstrap, and a fixed seed:
.PP
.RS
.nf
python montecarlo.py 1000000 65 M FL --quotes site --sims 2000 --model block --seed 1
.fi
.RE
.PP
Joint-life run capping real spending at 120% and flooring it at 50% of year 1:
.PP
.RS
.nf
python montecarlo.py 1000000 65 M FL --joint-age 63 --joint-gender F \\
    --upper-bound 1.2 --lower-bound 0.5
.fi
.RE
.SH FILES
.TP
.B montecarlo.py
This program. Exposes \fBbuild_report()\fR, the shared run-and-format entry point
used by both the command line and the Tk GUI.
.TP
.B montecarlo_gui.py
A Tcl/Tk front-end for this program: a form of the same inputs (with drop-downs
for the fixed-choice fields), a Submit button reachable by Tab and activated by
Enter, and Export PDF / Export CSV / Exit buttons. Run with a Python that has
tkinter, e.g. \fB~/finance/planning/.venv/bin/python montecarlo_gui.py\fR.
.TP
.B withdrawal_projection.py
Provides \fBbuild_rate_cache()\fR and \fBsimulate_path()\fR, reused for every path.
.TP
.B annuity_pricing.py
Local SOA-table annuity pricer (the default pricing source) and its mortality
tables \fBsoa_mortality_258{1,2}.csv\fR (base) and \fB258{3,4}.csv\fR (Scale G2).
.TP
.B equity_model.py
The equity-return / inflation models.
.TP
.B market_data.py
Embedded historical S&P 500 returns and CPI inflation, 1928\(en2025.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
Run with the project virtualenv, which provides NumPy:
.B ~/finance/planning/.venv/bin/python.
The default local pricing runs offline; network access to immediateannuities.com
is required only with \fB--quotes site\fR.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR withdrawal_projection (1),
.BR annuity_pricing (1),
.BR annuity_quote (1)
.SH AUTHOR
Generated for the personal finance planning workspace.
